	(199,NULL,NULL,2,'Piazza di Roma','piazza_di_roma','Piazza di Roma is a delightful, small, independent licenced ristorante situated at the top of Whiteladies Road in Clifton.','<p>Piazza di Roma is a delightful, small, independent licenced ristorante situated at the top of Whiteladies Road in Clifton.</p>\r\n<p>The Sicilian Head Chef/Owner serves only the most delicious authentic Italian cuisine to order, with passion and flair. Only the freshest and finest quality ingredients will do, and with over 30 years experience in very successful Italian restaurants, what he doesn\'t know about food isn\'t worth knowing.</p>\r\n<p>We have a specials board with a selection of starters and main courses that include fresh fish, beef steaks, lamb and vegetarian dishes.</p>\r\n<p>We provide a welcoming, warm, comfortable atmosphere in which to enjoy your meal, with friendly and efficient service.</p>\r\n<p>We offer a 10% discount for Takeaways.</p>','','BS8 2XU','51.4703224','-2.615590099999963',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00',14),
	(200,NULL,NULL,2,'Review: The Only Way Is Downton at Brewery Theatre, Bristol','review_the_only_way_is_downton_at_brewery_theatre_bristol','The Only Way Is Downton is a thousand times better than the real Downton Abbey','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">I think that&rsquo;s it, you might as well all give up. With The Only Way is Downton, Luke Kempner has won comedy theatre.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">With its implausible storylines, over-the-top acting and period drama intrigue, ITV&rsquo;s eternally popular Downton Abbey is ripe for parody. And with his one-man show The Only Way Is Downton, impressionist and actor Luke Kempner has definitely done that &ndash; rarely has theatre been more fun.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Fresh from a sell-out season at last year&rsquo;s Edinburgh Fringe, Kempner has since expanded the show with an extra 40 minutes and is taking it on tour around the UK. Bristol, I urge you to see this while you can.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Kempner has previously appeared in West End musicals such as Avenue Q and Les Mis, but now he&rsquo;s got the stage to himself &ndash; delightfully so in his one-man, full-cast song tonight. And this man is so genuinely talented that I feel sure it won&rsquo;t be long before the BBC is giving him his own Friday night show and hailing him as the successor to Alistair McGowan.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">There&rsquo;s trouble afoot at Grantham Abbey, as yet again the estate faces financial ruin and staff and gentry alike desperately try to find ways to save the show. And with Kempner&rsquo;s inspired mixing of contemporary reality TV shows with the period drama of Downton Abbey, he has a winning formula.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Throughout the gleefully implausible plot, we&rsquo;re repeatedly reminded that it&rsquo;s 1912 and told of many period details to keep us on track (Zips! Telephones! The Titanic!), while the cast also indulge in delightfully contemporary pursuits&hellip; none more so effective than Barrow&rsquo;s fanboy tweeting to Olympic diver Tom Daley. Although while watching The X Factor, Cora goes to ring in and vote, only to be reminded by Robert that it&rsquo;s 1912 and women can&rsquo;t vote for another six years. So she must sadly put the receiver down.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Whether Mrs Patmore and Daisy are competing in The Great British Bake Off, or Barrow and O&rsquo;Brian are chancing their luck on Pointless, the laughs keep coming. Although quite how Mr Bates snuck his way into the Wimbledon finals against Andy Murray is another story&hellip; but a damn funny one.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">As any Downton fan will attest (and I hold my hand up to being one), Kempner&rsquo;s impressions of the household are perfect. Lady Mary has her hands rigidly pointed outwards while she slowly enunciates all her syllables; the Dowager Countess repeatedly wrings her hands over her imaginary cane; Barrow is compulsively polishing an invisible object; and Mr Bates cannot stop himself from earnestly offering to commit a series of petty crimes. With every intonation, turn of phrase and physical gesture, Kempner has the cast spot on. And the knowing nods to actual Downton storylines are a treat&hellip; especially the repeated pleas for Cousin Matthew to definitely not go driving.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But Kempner&rsquo;s impressions don&rsquo;t stop there. Whether he&rsquo;s taking on Mel and Sue, Dermot O&rsquo;Leary, Alan Carr, John Bishop or Gary Barlow, Kempner remains pitch perfect. Although my favourite of all the many characters (I lost count of how many there were) was wretched Daisy, the whinging kitchen maid.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The Only Way Is Downton is a thousand times better than the real Downton Abbey&hellip; and I think the best thing that ITV could possibly do is commission Kempner to run the estate instead. However, I have just one question&hellip; Where&rsquo;s Anna?</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><em><strong>The Only Way Is Downton runs until 1 March, 2014, when it continues its tour around the UK. More info&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none;\" href=\"http://www.tobaccofactorytheatres.com/shows/detail/the_only_way_is_downton/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</strong></em></p>','','BS4 3EN','51.44363175468297','-2.495842968237298',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 11:17:38',0),
	(201,NULL,NULL,2,'Review: Barry Humphries Eat, Pray, Laugh at Bristol Hippodrome','review_barry_humphries_eat_pray_laugh_at_bristol_hippodrome','These are obviously well-worn gags but Humphriesâ€™ genius is to make them feel entirely spontaneous and appropriate.','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Don&rsquo;t go to this show if you&rsquo;re easily offended, and don&rsquo;t book a seat in the first couple of rows unless you enjoy some strange form of masochism. If you ignore my advice and get picked on by Dame Edna Everage (or &ldquo;liberated&rdquo; as Barry Humphries&rsquo; frightful Housewife Superstar prefers to call this process of humiliation) then don&rsquo;t say you weren&rsquo;t warned.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But for the rest of us, further back from the stage and even the &ldquo;paupers&rdquo; she refers to up in the gods, this is an evening of ripper entertainment. Watching Humphries make an audience laugh &ndash; and occasionally cry &ndash; is to witness a genius at work. And the worst news is that we might be running out of opportunities to go on doing so.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">His current show is based around three of his best established characters. Sir Les Patterson is just as vile, filthy and prejudiced (in every way &ndash; racist, homophobic, and misogynistic) as he ever has been. This time he farts, belches, spits and touches himself up throughout an extended slapstick sketch that has him auditioning to become Australia&rsquo;s next celebrity TV chef &ndash; and he doesn&rsquo;t let the fact that he&rsquo;s suffering from acute and rampant diarrhoea get in the way. Clearly the man and woman he invites up on stage to help him cook and eat did something dreadful in a previous life to deserve what they go through. She`s even made to scratch his ankle (shudder).</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The next Humphries creation on stage is Sandy Stone &ndash; a very different character indeed. Sandy is dead, a ghost, his ashes sprinkled by his wife over a piece of neighbourhood waste ground. At first it doesn&rsquo;t appear that he and his family had very eventful lives (&ldquo;We were never ones for going overseas. What&rsquo;s the point of going overseas when you don&rsquo;t even know your spare bedroom?&rdquo;) but gradually a quite dreadfully sad story &ndash; unapologetically sentimental &ndash; emerges and results in a good proportion of the audience shedding a few tears. It&rsquo;s never unbearably sad, but Sandy&rsquo;s character is the filling in the sandwich between Sir Les and Dame Edna &ndash; the darkness that helps them shine more brightly. Neither would be so spectacular without his contribution to the evening. This section is not only brilliantly written by Humphries (it&rsquo;s developed a lot over the years) but also quite exquisitely handled theatrically.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">And so it is finally time for Edna&rsquo;s arrival &ndash; time for those timid and too close to the stage to tremble and hope to avoid eye contact. What&rsquo;s clever about Edna is that she never actually tries to be nasty &ndash; it&rsquo;s just that she seems obliged to point out a few awkward home truths almost apologetically &ndash; like a socially inept old aunt. So it is that when discussing with one woman audience member just how much she has spent on her home Edna immediately sympathises, &ldquo;But at least you&rsquo;ve saved on clothes&rdquo;. These are obviously well-worn gags but Humphries&rsquo; genius (that word again) is to make them feel entirely spontaneous and appropriate.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Because Eat, Pray, Laugh sees Edna on a journey of spiritual enlightenment her most audacious sketch is to attempt a &ldquo;social experiment&rdquo; to bring two members of the audience &ndash; two complete strangers &ndash; together in a &ldquo;marriage ceremony&rdquo; because she`s identified them as being perfectly spiritually matched.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">On the opening night Edna could not have chosen two more unlikely people &ndash; it was a proposed match potentially full of quite jaw-dropping inappropriateness. Even with all her years of manipulating a crowd Humphries must have experienced a few concerns &ndash; could Edna really pull this one off?</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">I believe the audience was terrified for both Edna and the lovely couple of &ldquo;victims&rdquo; she&rsquo;d now chosen. If this went wrong it would be a car crash. But we needn&rsquo;t have worried. With consummate skill Humphries made everything a glorious success &ndash; the routine ended happily, satisfyingly and we all felt the couple were active players in the sequence &ndash; never the butt of the joke, never being laughed at.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">This is a wonderfully produced, crisply rehearsed, top-notch, professional show. If you can&rsquo;t buy a ticket anymore then beg or steal one &ndash; you won&rsquo;t be disappointed and I predict it will be one of the best shows you&rsquo;ll see at The Hippodrome all year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Humphries ended the night &ldquo;as himself&rdquo;, looking every inch the grand old man of the theatre dressed in a velvet smoking jacket and delivering an unusually personal message. He told us how he couldn&rsquo;t imagine performing a farewell tour that didn&rsquo;t include The Bristol Hippodrome and before we could dismiss that as the usual &ldquo;Luvvie Hogwash&rdquo; followed it up with a story of how the stage-door man had only that morning reminded him that the last time he performed there was 27 years ago.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Barry Humphries is now 80 years old and the only other UK dates in this farewell tour are in Leeds and Manchester &ndash; so not only should Bristol feel very, very fortunate to have him this might well be the last or only chance many of us will ever have of seeing him perform live.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.482828161917624','-2.628451381933587',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00',0),
